03518nam a22005535i 9780300133783DE-B159720220524034747.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220524t20082008ctu    fo  d z      eng d  a97803001337837 a10.12987/97803001337832doi  a(DE-B1597)485436  a(OCoLC)1024004654  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  actucUS-CT 4aPS201b.D665 2005eb 7aLIT0000002bisacsh04a810.9/0032221 aDonoghue, Denis, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut14aThe American Classics :bA Personal Essay /cDenis Donoghue. 1aNew Haven, CT : bYale University Press, c[2008] 4c©2008  a1 online resource (304 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aHow is a classic book to be defined? How much time must elapse before a work may be judged a “classic”? And among all the works of American literature, which deserve the designation? In this provocative new book Denis Donoghue essays to answer these questions. He presents his own short list of “relative” classics--works whose appeal may not be universal but which nonetheless have occupied an important place in our culture for more than a century. These books have survived the abuses of time-neglect, contempt, indifference, willful readings, excesses of praise, and hyperbole.Donoghue bestows the term classic on just five American works: Melville’s Moby-Dick, Hawthorne’s The Scarlet Letter, Thoreau’s Walden, Whitman’s Leaves of Grass, and Twain’s Adventures of Huckleberry Finn.Examining each in a separate chapter, he discusses how the writings have been received and interpreted, and he offers his own contemporary readings, suggesting, for example, that in the post-9/11 era, Moby-Dick may be rewardingly read as a revenge tragedy. Donoghue extends an irresistible invitation to open the pages of these American classics again, demonstrating with wit and acuity how very much they have to say to us now.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Mai 2022) 0aAmerican literaturexHistory and criticismxTheory, etcx19th century. 0aAmerican literaturey19th centuryxHistory and criticismxTheory, etc. 0aCanon (Literature). 0aChefs-d'œuvre (Littérature). 0aLittérature américainexHistoire et critiquexThéorie, etcx19e siècle. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertYale University Press Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013z978311053799440uhttps://doi.org/10.12987/978030013378340uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780300133783423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780300133783/original  a978-3-11-053799-4  Yale University Press Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_FAO  aEBA_UCA_YUP  aGBV-deGruyter-alles